    <div id="FeatureNFees">

   
    

        <div id="Features">
            <h2>Features</h2>
            <table>
            
                <tr >
                    <th>Portable
                    
                            <a class="help inlinehelp helpfeature" href="#" title="">help</a>
                            <span class="helptxt hidden">This mortgage will allow you to port the mortgage balance, or a reduced balance, subject to any applicable Early Repayment Charge.  If you need additional borrowing to purchase your next property, you'll be able to apply for the additional amount from the product range available at that time.</span>
                        
                        
                    </th>
                    <td>Yes</td>    
                </tr>
                
                <tr class='odd'>
                    <th>Overpayments
                    
                            <a class="help inlinehelp helpfeature" href="#" title="">help</a>
                            <span class="helptxt hidden">During the early repayment charge period, you can make repayments of up to 10% of the outstanding balance in each calendar year. </span>
                        
                        
                    </th>
                    <td>Up to 10% per calendar year</td>    
                </tr>
                
                <tr >
                    <th>Payment Holidays
                    
                            <a class="help inlinehelp helpfeature" href="#" title="">help</a>
                            <span class="helptxt hidden">You can apply for a one month payment holiday for every nine consecutive full monthly payments you make. The maximum payment holiday period is three months, which can be applied for once you have made 27 consecutive full monthly payments. The number of consecutive monthly payments is reset to zero if you don’t make a full monthly payment.</span>
                        
                        
                    </th>
                    <td>Yes<sup>1</sup></td>    
                </tr>
                
                <tr class='odd'>
                    <th>Interest Calculated
                    
                            <a class="help inlinehelp helpfeature" href="#" title="">help</a>
                            <span class="helptxt hidden">Interest is calculated daily so that as soon as your balance is reduced,  interest is only charged on what's outstanding.</span>
                        
                        
                    </th>
                    <td>Daily</td>    
                </tr>
                
            </table>
        </div>

        <div id="Fees">
            <h2>Fees</h2>
            <table>
            
                <tr >
                    <th>Product Fee
                    
                            <a class="help inlinehelp helpfee" href="#" title="">help</a>
                            <span class="helptxt hidden">We don't charge a product fee on this mortgage. </span>
                        
                        
                    </th>
                    <td>None</td>    
                </tr>
                
                <tr class='odd'>
                    <th>Application Fee
                    
                            <a class="help inlinehelp helpfee" href="#" title="">help</a>
                            <span class="helptxt hidden">The application fee is paid when you apply. This covers the cost of us processing your mortgage.</span>
                        
                        
                    </th>
                    <td>£99</td>    
                </tr>
                
                <tr >
                    <th>Early Repayment Charge
                    
                            <a class="help inlinehelp helpfee" href="#" title="">help</a>
                            <span class="helptxt hidden">An Early Repayment Charge is a charge you may have to pay if you leave (by paying back your mortgage early and/or moving to another lender) while you're in any special rate period. This may also apply if you overpay more than you are allowed.</span>
                        
                        
                    </th>
                    <td>5% of outstanding balance</td>    
                </tr>
                
                <tr class='odd'>
                    <th>Valuation Fee
                    
                            <a class="help inlinehelp helpfee" href="#" title="">help</a>
                            <span class="helptxt hidden">There are three main reports you can choose from: a Mortgage Valuation Report, a HomeBuyer Report and a Building Survey, which is formerly known as a Structural Survey.</span>
                        
                        
                    </th>
                    <td>Refer to <a href="/Mortgages/learn/first-time-buyer/mortgage-costs/#valuation" onclick="openPopup('/mortgages/Learn/First-Time-Buyer/Mortgage-Costs/#valuation', 'mortgage_costs'); return false;">valuation fee</a> scale</td>    
                </tr>
                
                <tr >
                    <th>Legal Fees
                    
                            <a class="help inlinehelp helpfee" href="#" title="">help</a>
                            <span class="helptxt hidden">When you buy a home, you will need to pay a solicitor or qualified conveyancer for the legal work required. This will include checking the title to the property, preparing the mortgage documents, receiving the money to pay for the purchase, paying it to the seller's solicitor, and negotiating with the seller's solicitor in the event of any dispute. It pays to shop around on price and service. We can recommend a conveyancer to use, if you wish. Most conveyancers will be happy to provide a no obligation quote.</span>
                        
                        
                    </th>
                    <td>Can vary</td>    
                </tr>
                
            </table>
        </div>

